player.seasonOutlook: Hubbard was selected in the fourth round of the 2021 draft and, much like Mike Davis the year prior, he was asked to soak up significant snaps in place of an injured Christian McCaffrey. Hubbard was not overly impressive in the role, ranking near the basement of the league in YPC (3.6), YAC (1.3) and YPT (5.0) while pacing all backs in drops (seven). He failed to post a weekly fantasy finish better than 15th and deferred substantial playing time to scat back Ameer Abdullah in the second half of the season. Perhaps Hubbard will make a Year 2 leap, but even if McCaffrey misses more time, the 23-year-old will need to compete with newcomer D'Onta Foreman for work. Hubbard belongs on waivers.

Wilson signed a three-year, $22 million contract with Miami after spending his first four seasons in Dallas. The deal was a bit of an eyebrow-raiser considering Wilson was a former sixth-round pick who has been limited to a backup/situational role during his career. In fact, Wilson has 96 targets in his career, 61 of which came in 2021. In Wilson's defense, he was pretty good last season, ranking no lower than 13th among wide receivers in catch rate (74%), yards per target (9.9) and RAC (5.8). The 26-year-old aligned in the slot on 79% of his routes in Dallas and figures to see similar usage between Tyreek Hill and Jaylen Waddle in Miami. Wilson is a long shot for consistent production with Hill, Waddle and Mike Gesicki higher in priority, but he's a name to monitor in deep formats.

Crowder signed with Buffalo after spending his first seven seasons with the Commanders and Jets. The 2015 fourth-round pick has some limitations, including a lack of work near the goal line (25 career end zone targets), a role limited to the short range (career 7.5 average depth of target) and shaky durability (at least four missed games three of the last four seasons). He's been busy when healthy, though, posting a target share of at least 17% each of the last five seasons. He has a path to a share in that range again this season as the team's replacement for Cole Beasley in the slot. Crowder is 29 years old and has never had a top-25 fantasy campaign, so while his ceiling is limited, Buffalo's elite, pass-heavy offense is enough to make him worth a late-round flier.

Davis-Price was selected by the 49ers in the third round of April's draft. The LSU product soaked up 379 carries and 40 targets during three seasons with the Tigers. He was busiest as a rusher last season (211-1003-6 rushing line), but never quite emerged as a threat in the passing game (season high of 15 targets). Davis-Price's rushing and receiving efficiency were both poor during his career and that includes low-end showings in the YAC and FMT departments. He posted a decent 40 time (4.48) at the combine, but underwhelmed in the vertical and broad jump. He's young and has some tools, so there's some upside here, but playing time will elude him after Elijah Mitchell emerged as the team's lead back as a rookie in 2021. Davis-Price's primary value is in dynasty.

Williams signed with Atlanta and will compete with Cordarrelle Patterson and rookie Tyler Allgeier for backfield snaps. Williams was limited to 56 touches in Chicago last season and has now fallen below 75 touches in six of his seven pro seasons. He was fantasy-relevant while working in the high-scoring Kansas City offense in 2019 and theoretically has a path to a generous share of the touches in one of the league's shakiest backfields. That said, it's possible he sees enough work to flirt with occasional flex value, but especially considering he's now 30 years old, it's very likely that he'll settle in as a situational player. Williams should only be considered late in very deep leagues.

Edwards is back competing for work in the Baltimore backfield after missing all of 2021 with a torn ACL. Edwards became an afterthought when the Ravens selected J.K. Dobbins in the second round of the 2020 draft, but it turned out to be a mistake to overlook a young back with a career 5.2 YPC. Edwards racked up 852 yards and six TDs from scrimmage while pacing Baltimore's backfield in carries (144) and touches (153). Dobbins will be the lead man in 2022, but he's also coming off a torn ACL and isn't yet established as an NFL lead back. Edwards figures to clear 100 carries, but a miniscule role as a receiver (24 targets in 43 games) pushes him off the flex radar. He's best valued as insurance behind Dobbins.

Hilliard returns to Tennessee and will compete with fourth-round rookie Hassan Haskins for situational reps behind feature back Derrick Henry. Hilliard didn't play a single snap in the first half of last season, but leapt to a 40% snap share (8.0 carries and 3.6 targets per game) when Henry was sidelined during Weeks 11 to 18. Hilliard was effective on the ground (6.3 YPC), but not as a receiver (3.5 YPT) and was 37th among RBs in fantasy PPG during the stretch. The 27-year-old will remain a change-of-pace back, even if Henry misses time, and does not need to be drafted.

Perine is back with Cincinnati as the favorite for primary backup duties behind Joe Mixon. He's played that role the last two seasons, which has allowed rushing lines of 63-301-3 and 55-246-1, as well as receiving lines of 11-66-0 and 27-196-1. Perine's efficiency has been solid in recent years, but he has yet to produce a top-40 fantasy campaign in his five-year career. He can be expected to see a handful of touches each game this season and, should Mixon miss time, he'd lead a committee that would also include passing-down specialist Chris Evans. Perine is worth holding only if you roster Mixon in a very deep league.

Scott returns for his fifth season in Philadelphia and will resume his role as a situational player behind Miles Sanders and perhaps second-year man Kenneth Gainwell. The scatback has logged 61-to-87 carries and 85-to-105 touches each of the last three seasons, falling outside the top 45 RBs in fantasy points all three years. Scott is effective in his role (career 4.4 YPC, 6.2 YPT) and -- believe it or not -- has led the RB position in rushing TD rate two of the last three seasons (min. 50 carries), but he's on the small side and unlikely to ever be more than a change-of-pace back. Barring an injury to Sanders, the 27-year-old should be on waivers.

Breida signed with the Giants and is the favorite for No. 2 duties behind Saquon Barkley.  The veteran back made stops in San Francisco and Miami before playing a backup role in Buffalo last season. The speedy Breida has generally been limited to a committee role, but he's been effective, posting a career 4.9 YPC and 6.6 YPT. His peak was a 26th-place fantasy campaign in 2018 (1,075 yards on 180 touches), though he hasn't otherwise posted a top-45 finish. The 27-year-old will be worth adding only if Barkley misses time, and even then a committee would be likely.

Okwuegbunam was the big winner of the Russell Wilson/Noah Fant trade, as the third-year tight end will have much-improved QB play while also replacing Fant as Denver's No. 1 tight end. The 2020 fourth-round pick has flashed in 18 career games; his 7.2 RAC ranks first and his 80% catch rate third among 51 tight ends with 50-plus targets over the last two seasons. Okwuegbunam very well could cap out as a TE2, especially with third-round rookie Greg Dulcich in the mix and with Denver so strong at wide receiver, but a full-on third-year breakout is certainly possible. Consider Okwuegbunam with one of your final picks.

Wentz was traded to Washington after spending one season with the Colts. His 2021 showing was a big step forward after a rough 2020 with Philadelphia, but he still wasn't much of a fantasy factor, finishing 13th despite appearing in all 17 games. Volume was a problem in Indianapolis' run-heavy offense and, while that may change in Washington, it may not be enough to overcome mediocre efficiency and rushing contributions. Wentz will benefit from a good offensive line and solid supporting cast led by Terry McLaurin, but he's a long shot to deliver what would be his third career top-12 fantasy campaign. He's a fringe QB2.

Bourne was an unheralded UDFA signing by San Francisco back in 2017 and he has continued to improve during his five seasons in the league. Bourne took another leap forward in 2021 -- his first in New England -- setting career highs in receptions, receiving yards and fantasy points. He is extremely efficient (his 79% catch rate and 11.4 YPT ranked third and his 6.9 RAC sixth among wide receivers in 2021) and his 33rd-place fantasy finish would've been better if not for almost no goal-line work (one end zone target). As good as Bourne played, the 27-year-old seems stuck in a situational role and that is doubtful to change with Jakobi Meyers and Nelson Agholor back and DeVante Parker and Tyquan Thornton added to the mix. Bourne does not need to be drafted.

Doubs was selected by Green Bay in the fourth round of April's draft. Doubs is a vertical, perimeter receiver with good size, speed and hands. He aligned on the perimeter 85% of the time at Nevada and ran a deep route 43% of the time (second highest in this rookie class). He was never short for volume, having seen 75-plus targets in each of his four seasons. Doubs finished his career with 58-1002-9 and 80-1109-11 receiving lines, having cleared 24% of the team targets and 39% of the air yards both seasons. Doubs was also a standout punt returner. The Packers' WR situation is wide open, so if Doubs develops quickly, he could play significant snaps as a rookie. Keep him stashed in dynasty and monitor his progress this summer.

Hamler is entering his third NFL season after his 2021 campaign was derailed by a torn ACL suffered in Week 3. The 2020 second-round pick had produced 74 yards on 10 targets prior to the injury. Hamler made some noise as a rookie (30-381-3 receiving line), but his efficiency was very poor; he ranked near the basement in catch rate (53%), YPT (6.7), YPRR (1.2) and drop rate (8.8%). Hamler is a small (5-foot-9, 178 pounds) and fast slot WR who has competition for targets with Courtland Sutton and Jerry Jeudy ahead of him on the depth chart. The arrival of Russell Wilson helps his cause, but Hamler has a tough path to consistent fantasy value. Consider the 23-year-old in the later rounds.

Wilson is entering his second NFL season after a rocky rookie campaign in which he struggled with efficiency and missed four games with an injury. The 2021 second-overall pick was limited to nine passing TDs and 11 INTs and ranked among the worst QBs in completion rate (56%), YPA (6.1), sack rate (10.3%) and drop rate (6.3%). Poor rookie-season pass efficiency isn't a major concern, so a big second-year leap is very possible. Wilson added some value with legs (including four TDs) as a rookie and his 2022 prospects are heightened by an improved supporting cast led by Elijah Moore and early-round rookies Garrett Wilson and Breece Hall. Same as most high-pedigree, second-year QBs, Wilson is worth late-round consideration.

Believe it or not, Tannehill has finished as a top-12 fantasy QB each of the past two seasons. However, we saw a pretty large step back in his production in 2021. Tannehill fell from 33 passing TDs in 2020 to 21 last season, while his INTs doubled (seven to 14) and his sack total nearly did as well (24 to 47). He finished 15th in fantasy PPG after top-10 showings the prior two seasons. Tannehill suffers a bit from Tennessee's extremely run-heavy offense, though he's made up some ground with seven rushing TDs each of the last two seasons. Especially with A.J. Brown gone, Tannehill is best viewed as a QB2 and won't be anything more than an occasional streaming option in most formats.

Miami's D/ST is one of three units to finish top eight in fantasy points each of the last two seasons. That includes a fourth in 2021. The Dolphins predictably saw a dip in INTs last season after pacing the NFL with 18 in 2020, but made up for it with more sacks and six TDs. Fifteen Miami defenders played 400-plus snaps last season and all 15 remain on the 2022 roster. That includes elite CB duo Xavien Howard and Byron Jones, as well as key contributors Christian Wilkins, Jerome Baker, Emmanuel Ogbah and emerging star Jevon Holland. Miami has been dependent on big plays and has a new coaching staff this season, but this is nonetheless a solid unit with upside. Consider it a fringe fantasy starting option.

Cleveland made major defensive additions last offseason and the result was the best fantasy campaign by its D/ST in over a decade (13th). The unit was near mid-pack in most categories, but shined in sacks (ninth most), pass rush win rate (third best) and yards allowed (fifth fewest). Cleveland wasn't as aggressive this past offseason, but it didn't need to be, with 10 of the top 12 in 2021 snaps back on the roster. The unit has stars (Myles Garrett, Denzel Ward, John Johnson III), as well as several emerging recent early-round picks (Jeremiah Owusu-Koramoah, Greg Newsome II, Grant Delpit). Adding Jakeem Grant also helps, as he has at least one return TD in five of his six pro seasons. Cleveland's D/ST has the look of a good streaming option.

Jones was selected by Chicago in the third round of April's draft. Jones is one of the oldest receivers in this rookie class (turned 25 in May), having spent four years at USC (52 catches) and two more at Tennessee (84 catches). He wasn't much of a factor as a receiver during most of his collegiate career, but "broke out" in 2021 with a 62-807-7 receiving line while working as a short area (6.9 aDOT) slot receiver. He impressed at the combine with the top 40-yard dash (4.31) and speed score (118) at the position. Jones is a special teams standout, though he's likely to be needed often on offense in 2022 with the likes of Byron Pringle and Dazz Newsome next up behind Darnell Mooney. He's worth considering with a late pick.

Westbrook-Ikhine is positioned for a significant role for Tennessee this season following the offseason departure of A.J. Brown. The 2020 UDFA signing is unlikely to be any lower than third on the depth chart and could rise as high as No. 1 depending on the development of first-round pick Treylon Burks and health of Robert Woods (ACL recovery). Westbrook-Ikhine was serviceable on 632 snaps last season, posting a solid 8.1 yards per target, but he wasn't a fantasy option, managing two weekly finishes better than 30th and none better than 18th. The 25-year-old is a long shot for consistent flex production in Tennessee's run-heavy scheme. He's best left on waivers.

Osborn was a pleasant surprise for Minnesota last season, emerging as a viable No. 3 wide receiver behind Justin Jefferson and Adam Thielen. The 2020 fifth-round pick went from not playing a snap as a rookie to finishing 32nd at the position in routes and 40th in fantasy points in his second season.  After hit-or-miss production in the first half of the season, Osborn's production was much better when he stepped into an every-down role in place of an injured Thielen during Weeks 13-18. Osborn scored in five of the six games and was 18th in fantasy points during the span. The 25-year-old is a good bet for more snaps in new coach Kevin O'Connell's WR-friendly offense, though he's likely to need a Jefferson or Thielen injury in order to land in the flex discussion.

Beckham remains a free agent. He continues to show up with spurts of greatness, but injuries have derailed his career. Beckham has played two full seasons in his career and has appeared in 53 of 81 possible games (65%) over the last five seasons. Beckham's latest injury was a torn ACL suffered in the Super Bowl, an injury that makes him a long shot to be ready for the first weeks (if not months) of the 2022 season. Beckham was fantasy's No. 22 WR during seven full games with the Rams last season, so there's hope for fantasy-relevance once he's back, but that's not enough to consider the 29-year-old prior to the final few rounds of your draft.

Injuries have been a problem for Shepard throughout his six-year career, but he finally seemed to be over the hump and blooming into a star late in 2020 and into early 2021. He finished 2020 with 9-77-1 and 8-112-1 receiving lines and opened last season with 7-113-1 and 9-94-0 lines. But then the injuries struck again, limiting Shepard to five games prior to yet another major setback -- a torn Achilles in Week 15. Shepard has seen at least six targets in 31 of his last 35 games (8.0 average), but he's also missed at least four games each of the last four seasons. Shepard has yet finish a season better than 30th in fantasy points and he's now 28 years old and coming off a major injury. Even when healthy, he'll be tough to count on and, thus, is best left on waivers.

After one-year stops in Dallas and Houston, Cobb was traded back to Green Bay (his home for his first eight NFL seasons) prior to 2021. Unsurprisingly, the reunion with Aaron Rodgers didn't lead to much fantasy success. Cobb was limited to 39 targets while primarily working in a situational role. He also missed five games and hasn't played a full season since he was 25 years old back in 2015. Cobb is now entering his age-32 campaign and hasn't been a top-40 fantasy receiver since 2017. He theoretically has a path to more work with Davante Adams gone, but that seems like a long shot considering his age and durability woes, as well as the acquisitions of Sammy Watkins, Christian Watson and Romeo Doubs. Cobb can be avoided in all but the deepest of PPR leagues.

Davis is back for his second season in New York, after struggling with durability and performance in 2021. The 2017 first-round pick appeared in only nine games and he's now missed at least one game in four of five NFL seasons. Davis has also underwhelmed from a fantasy perspective, having yet to clear five TDs in a season or finish top 30 in fantasy PPG. His 10.2% drop rate was the worst at the position in 2021. Perhaps the 27-year-old will make the leap back into the flex discussion if QB Zach Wilson makes a huge second-year leap, but there's not much upside with Elijah Moore and first-round rookie Garrett Wilson in the mix. Davis belongs on benches, if not waivers.

Green re-signed with Arizona after a relatively successful 2021 campaign with the team. Green played 80% of the snaps during 16 active games and his 54-848-3 receiving line allowed a 41st-place finish in fantasy. He was primarily utilized as an intermediate/deep threat and his 15.7 YPR was 10th highest among wideouts. Green has ranked no lower than 13th at the position in end zone targets each of his last four seasons. He will play a lesser role this season after the acquisition of Marquise Brown, though he'll see a boost in work during DeAndre Hopkins' six-game suspension to open the season. Green's upside is limited at age 34, but he figures to hang on the flex radar while Hopkins is out.

Benjamin is back with Arizona, though following Chase Edmonds' departure, the former seventh-round pick has a shot for No. 2 duties behind James Conner. Benjamin will compete with the likes of Darrel Williams, Jonathan Ward and sixth-round rookie Keaontay Ingram for change-of-pace duties. The 23-year-old appeared in eight games last season and produced a weak 160 yards on 40 touches. He's on the small side and doesn't ever figure to be tasked with a full workload, which severely limits his fantasy ceiling. Benjamin is only worth adding to your roster if Conner is out with an injury.

Vaughn is entering his third NFL season and the 2020 third-round pick is positioned for a larger role behind Leonard Fournette after Ronald Jones II's departure. Vaughn hasn't been asked to do much so far (62 carries and 18 targets in 16 career games), but he's been effective in a small sample: his 2.8 YAC is tops among 98 RBs with at least 60 carries over the last two seasons. The 25-year-old doesn't have standalone fantasy value, especially with passing-down specialist Giovani Bernard in the mix, but he'd likely be the lead back in the event of a Fournette injury, which would launch him into, at least, the RB2 mix. Assuming he fends off rookie Rachaad White, Vaughn will be a fine bench option.

Gaskin was a solid find by Miami in the seventh round of the 2019 draft, but the 25-year-old is headed for a reduced role in 2022. Gaskin has finished among the top 23 backs in touches and fantasy points each of the past two seasons, but Miami changed coaching staffs and signed RBs Raheem Mostert, Chase Edmonds and Sony Michel during the offseason. That leaves Gaskin without much of a role, though it isn't a surprising development after he ranked dead last in yards per target (3.7) and near the basement in yards per carry (3.5) and yards after contact (1.5) last season. Gaskin should not be drafted.

Evans is entering his second NFL season looking to unseat veteran Samaje Perine as Joe Mixon's primary backup. Evans -- a 2021 sixth-round pick -- impressed in a situational passing-down role as a rookie. He played only 91 snaps, but turned 17 carries into 77 yards (4.5 YPC) and 17 targets into 151 yards and two touchdowns (8.9 YPT). That includes a Week 18 game in which he produced 59 yards and a score on 11 touches as the lead back. Evans has no standalone fantasy value and, should Mixon miss time, he'd likely slide in as the team's primary receiving back, with Perine ticketed for most of the carries and goal line work. Evans doesn't need to be drafted.

Haskins was selected by the Titans in the fourth round of April's draft. Haskins is a large (228 pounds), tough (27 bench reps)downhill runner, whose size doesn't allow much speed and elusiveness. He racked up a hefty 270 carries at Michigan last season and, while he rarely lost yardage (class-best 8.5% of carries), he produced 5-plus yards only 33% of the time (third worst). Haskins' YAC and FMT rates were both below average and he wasn't overly impressive on 22 targets. Haskins ran for 30 TDs in three seasons and is the only back in the class without a single collegiate fumble (on 476 career touches). He's reliable, but not dynamic. Haskins is a natural D'Onta Foreman replacement and would share the backfield with Dontrell Hilliard in the event of a Derrick Henry injury. He has some insurance appeal.

Ryan was traded to the Colts after spending his first 14 seasons with the Falcons. He has delivered the occasional big fantasy season during his career (second place in 2016 and 2018), but he's also finished 11th or worse five of the last seven seasons despite often ranking near the top of the league in pass attempts. That's especially a concern as he heads to a run-heavy Indianapolis offense that will continue to lean heavily on Jonathan Taylor. Ryan is now 37 years old and has never cleared 147 rushing yards in a single season. He's an upgrade for the Colts, but is not in a good spot from a fantasy perspective. Consider him a fringe QB2 with limited upside.

Jones was the fifth QB selected in the 2021 draft, but no rookie passer was more impressive last season. The Alabama product was, at worst, average in notable categories like QBR (51.0), YPA (7.3) and completion rate (68%), the latter of which was eighth best in the league. The bad news is that Jones unsurprisingly was a nonfactor with his legs (15 scrambles in 17 games). His fantasy production was extremely boom/bust and included five top-10 weeks, as well as 10 finishes of 22nd or worse. Jones will need elite passing numbers in order to reach QB1 status, and while that's possible (adding DeVante Parker helps), it's obviously unlikely. He's worth no more than a late-round flier.

Goff is back as the starting QB in Detroit. The ex-Ram appeared in 14 games last season and was limited to one weekly fantasy finish better than eighth (Week 1) and two others better than 12th. Goff was extremely conservative, as his 6.5 average depth of throw was lowest in the NFL. It's possible that increases with improved targets this season, but that's far from a lock considering he was at 6.4 in his final season with the Rams. Goff is also a non-factor as a rusher, having yet to clear 108 rushing yards in a single season. He's barely on the QB2 radar.

Everett signed with the Chargers after four seasons with the Rams and a one-year stop in Seattle. Incredibly, Everett's reception and yardage totals have increased every season he's been in the league. He also posted career-high marks in targets, touchdowns and catch rate (75%) last season. Everett has generally been utilized as a short-range target (career 6.7 aDOT) and not much near the goal line (18 career end zone targets), which has left him without a top-20 fantasy campaign. Of course, he's now positioned as the top receiving tight end in an elite Chargers' offense. The 28-year-old is in the TE2 mix and has some late-round appeal.

Thomas enters 2022 eyeing a rebound campaign after last season was derailed by multiple injuries. Thomas was seventh in fantasy points through three weeks before a hamstring injury knocked him out until Week 12. He returned for two games before suffering a torn ACL. Thomas is now 31 years old and his early-season availability and effectiveness are in question, but he's a good bet to return to the TE1 mix when healthy. In his breakout 2021, Thomas led all tight ends in snaps and routes on his way to a 72-670-6 receiving line and a third-place fantasy finish. Thomas' recovery will need to be monitored throughout the offseason.

Tonyan entered last season as the poster boy for regression to the mean, and boy did he take that to heart. One season after posting a 52-586-11 receiving line in 16 games, Tonyan plummeted to 18-204-2 in eight games prior to suffering a torn ACL. Tonyan's huge dip in scoring is obvious, but his catch rate (88% to 62%) and YPT (9.9 to 7.0) also crashed back to earth. His targets were almost identical during the two seasons (3.7 in 2020, 3.6 in 2021) and so, even with Davante Adams gone, it's hard to expect much of an increase this season. The 28-year-old will have some touchdown upside as long as Aaron Rodgers is his quarterback, but he's best viewed as a mid-to-back-end TE2.

Alie-Cox heads into the 2022 season with what is perhaps his best opportunity at a breakout following the offseason retirement of Jack Doyle. To this point, Alie-Cox has maxed out at 45 targets (2021), 394 yards (2020) and four touchdowns (2021), but coach Frank Reich has a lengthy history of heavy tight end usage. In his eight seasons as a coordinator/playcaller, he's had eight TE units reach a 20% target share (26% average). Alie-Cox has yet to produce a top-25 fantasy campaign, but he's a vertical target (9.6 aDOT last season) in a TE-friendly scheme with minimal competition for snaps ( recent mid-round picks Kylen Granson and Jelani Woods). The 28-year-old is a viable sleeper target in deeper leagues.
